<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hick; Bill Billiter, , RREN, ; Debra Cano 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 HAULIN' FOOT: If you see 13 men and one woman running near Pacific Coast 
Highway in Huntington Beach before daylight today, your feet might ache just 
thinking about what's ahead of them. They're taking off in a multi-company 
sponsored Trans America foot race, which will wind up 3,000 miles and 64 days 
later at New York City's Central Park.In two previous annual races, half the 
field failed to make it.... Officials figure it at 4 million footsteps and 
nearly half a million burned up calories. 
</P>
<P>
 KEY TO CITY: Seal Beach has jail space to rent, and Cypress is among the 
cities interested. Cypress Police Chief Daryl Wicker contends it would be 
considerably cheaper than the $159 per prisoner the city pays for an Orange 
County Jail booking.... When City Council members this week asked Wicker if the 
city would be locked in the new arrangement with Seal Beach proved unsuitable, 
he said straight-faced: "We would have an escape clause." 
</P>
<P>
 HOLE-IN-CLOSE: Remember that hole-in-one contest in Huntington Beach where you 
could win $1million for an ace at Meadowlark Golf Course? The city was insured 
just in case, of course. Nobody won, but Jeff Stewart of Fountain Valley did 
get close to the pin -- about nine feet -- in the recent contest.... And the 
consolation prize wasn't bad -- a trip to Paris for two. Says Stewart: "I was 
happy with the shot because I knew it would be tough to beat." The event raised 
$8,000 to benefit the city's Fourth of July celebration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
