<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCHOOLS BUDGET CALLS FOR NO MAJOR CUTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JON NALICK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The governing board of the Westminster School District has approved its 
1994-95 budget, which calls for no significant cuts in programs or staff for 
the first time in four years. 
</P>
<P>
 The Board of Education approved the $35-million spending plan without comment 
at its regular meeting on Thursday.It proposes a 2% raise for classified 
personnel, and no change in the current level of staffing or programs. 
</P>
<P>
 In previous years, the district was forced to cut $3 million in programs and 
personnel because of plummeting funding from the state. Those cuts included the 
loss of school nurses, psychologists and teachers and resulted in larger class 
sizes, prompting bitter complaints from parents and school employees alike. 
</P>
<P>
 On Thursday, no one from the public spoke during the budget hearing. 
</P>
<P>
 "Our schools have had a really tough time for the past five years and its hard 
for anyone to work well under those conditions," district spokeswoman Audrey 
Brown said. "However, this is the first year that we're not deficit spending so 
we can breathe a little." JON NALICK 
</P>
</TEXT>
