<HEADLINE>
<P>
READERS SAY TYSON DESERVED DAY IN COURT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After reading Sigmund Downey's psychoanalytic hanging of Mike Tyson (June 13), 
I suggest you move his column to the Life & Style section. No one defends Mike 
Tyson as a model citizen, but it doesn't take a Ph.D. to figure out his 
conviction was not an uncontested slam dunk.He deserves his day in court 
without Dr. Downey taking Freudian cheap shots from 2,000 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
 MARC O'BRIEN 
</P>
<P>
 Malibu 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Tyson was not tried and convicted of being a "raging bully," nor for what he 
may or may not have done to his former wife, Robin Givens, nor for anything he 
may or may not have said to heavyweight Razor Ruddock. His sentence was 
rendered solely upon his conviction for the Desiree Washington rape charge. 
</P>
<P>
 GERALD M. SINGER 
</P>
<P>
 Encino 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 "Tyson cornered her like a foe. He overpowered her." Thank you, Mike Downey, 
for finally shedding light on this convoluted event. Up until this time I was 
under the impression that only Ms. Washington and Iron Mike were in the room 
that evening, but now the world knows that you were secretly hiding under the 
bed to get the story firsthand. 
</P>
<P>
 Now I will be the first to agree with you that Mike Tyson should remain in 
jail if he, in fact, did rape Desiree Washington. I can't say though that I'm 
convinced here. Society has demonstrated that a guilty verdict in court is not 
necessarily a revelation of truth, nor does a not-guilty verdict absolve 
accused parties of blame (see: Rodney King, Latasha Harlins, William Kennedy 
Smith, etc.) 
</P>
<P>
 MORRIS W. O'KELLY 
</P>
<P>
 Torrance 
</P>
</TEXT>
