<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94 / THE FIRST ROUND; SPOTLIGHT; FOR GERMAN TEAM, D-DAY IN 
REVERSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARJORIE MILLER, Times Bonn Bureau 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 From Bonn, Germany's General Anzeiger newspaper, Friday: 
</P>
<P>
 "A D-Day of Football?" 
</P>
<P>
 "That the world championship went to the United States is nothing but an 
attempt to eliminate that big white spot on the map of the FIFA. . . . It's a 
fact that there are 250 million potential customers for soccer shoes, T-shirts, 
balls, trinkets and more.A gigantic market to be developed. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 "The world championship beginning today offers the last chance to make King 
Soccer acceptable in the USA. If this goes by, the industry might not be 
mobilized again. But so far the organizers still dream that their world 
championship will be the detonator. Should it be so, then Lothar Matthaeus, 
Andreas Moeller & Co. will possibly return in 50 years as those who freed the 
country from the dictatorship of American football and baseball. And maybe then 
they will sit in Soldier Field in Chicago, where today the opening match takes 
place, and dream of June 17, 1994 -- the D-Day of Soccer." 
</P>
</TEXT>
